{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488744"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:54:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:54:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"522"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/522"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.11,0.13,0.49,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"522"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99923"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/522"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"522"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82315"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"444"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3416"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3576"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33536"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99923"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of inadvertently bumping into objects on his left side. He reports no other visual disturbances, headaches, or neurological symptoms. He has a medical history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. His medications include amlodipine and atorvastatin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination is unremarkable. Visual acuity is 6/6 bilaterally. Visual field testing shows a defect in the outer aspect of his left visual field and inner aspect of his right visual field.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely site of the underlying lesion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left optic nerve","Right optic nerve","Left visual cortex","Right visual cortex","Left optic radiation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a left homonymous hemianopia, which is a visual field defect affecting the same side (homonymous) of both eyes. Specifically, he has lost vision in the left half of his visual field in both eyes. This pattern localises the lesion to the right-sided visual pathway posterior to the optic chiasm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight visual cortex\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely site of the lesion in this case. A lesion in the right occipital lobe (visual cortex) would cause a left homonymous hemianopia as described in this patient. Common causes include stroke (particularly in the posterior cerebral artery territory), tumour, or trauma affecting the occipital lobe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft visual cortex\u003C/strong\u003E lesions would cause a right homonymous hemianopia (affecting the right visual field of both eyes), which is the opposite of what this patient is experiencing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft or right optic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E lesions would cause a complete loss of vision in the left or right eyes respectively, not a hemianopic defect affecting both eyes. Optic nerve lesions cause monocular visual loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft optic radiation\u003C/strong\u003E lesions would also cause a right-sided visual field defect. Depending on which portion of the optic radiation is affected, this could be a complete right homonymous hemianopia or a right upper or lower quadrantanopia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the visual pathway is crucial for localising neurological lesions. The visual pathway consists of the optic nerves, which partially cross at the optic chiasm, then continue as the optic tracts, which synapse in the lateral geniculate nucleus before continuing as the optic radiations to the visual cortex. Lesions at different points in this pathway produce characteristic visual field defects that help in neuroanatomical localization.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A right homonymous hemianopia is caused by a lesion in the left visual pathway posterior to the optic chiasm.","A left homonymous hemianopia is caused by a lesion in the right visual pathway posterior to the optic chiasm.","Visual field defects help localise neurological lesions based on the anatomy of the visual pathway."],"references":["Bowling, B. (2015). Kanski\u2019s clinical ophthalmology (8th ed.). W B Saunders"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82315"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"522"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82315"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-23T09:58:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-23T12:00:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"522"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99923"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"